## Severity
Minor
## Dimension
security
## Location
src/plugins/validate.rs:108-138
## Violation
The forbidden-char set is `['/', '\\', '\0', ':']` plus a `..` substring check. This is a partial Windows-aware allowlist but misses the reserved-name set (CON, PRN, AUX, NUL, COM1-9, LPT1-9), trailing dot/space (Windows strips them, enabling collision), and case-insensitive comparison. Quoted lines:

    let forbidden: &[char] = &['/', '\\', '\0', ':'];
    if name
        .chars()
        .any(|c| forbidden.contains(&c) || c.is_control())
    {
        return Err(PluginError::InvalidManifest(format!(
            "Derived directory name '{name}' contains path separator, NUL, or control character"
        )));
    }
    if name.contains("..") {
        return Err(PluginError::InvalidManifest(format!(
            "Derived directory name '{name}' contains '..'"
        )));
    }

A repository named `con.git` or `nul.git` (case-insensitive on Windows) materialises as a reserved device path, with undefined behaviour ranging from "fails opaquely" to "writes to the device". A name like `foo .git` (trailing space before .git) derives `foo ` and silently collides with `foo` on Windows.
## Mandated refactor
Add a Windows-reserved-name allowlist check (case-insensitive comparison against the documented set). Reject trailing dot or whitespace. Reject empty-after-trim. Cap derived names at 64 chars. Consider running everything through a `slug` crate to produce a single canonical form regardless of the platform.
